You're saying that the fact that a nation tests chemical &amp; biological weapons programmes means they're going to use them?  Of course it doesn't- the US tests nuclear weapons, hasn't signed the CTBT and is the only nation ever to have used nuclear weapons.  Yet I can't forsee the United States ever using nuclear weapons except in retaliation.  Numerous nations test and maintain secret weapons programmes- the fact that these weapons are being developed doesn't mean that they are a threat, nor does it mean they would ever be used.  There is such a thing as the deterrence factor y'know- claiming that the *only* reason a nation would develop a secret WMD programme is to strike first...is more than a little naive.<br>
<br>
My &quot;prove it&quot; statement was directed at anyone proving that either containment or deterrence had failed.  The US and other permanent members with nuclear arsenals, plus the nuclear arsenal Israel possesses- these <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>all</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> deter Saddam from ever using any alleged WMD.  Smawty, it's not about understanding &quot;the mind of a brutal dictator&quot;.  It's about tried and tested policy- the deterrence of a nation state.  It doesn't matter how insane or power-hungry a dictator is, unless they're suicidal.  Guess what, Saddam's regime is not suicidal, it's in fact a good deal *less* suicidal than the USSR ever was in the long history of deterrence.  There is no way he'd use any WMD he <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>might</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> have in a useable state because that would guarantee his destruction.  I don't know how much simpler I can make the policy of deterrence- it works, and history shows it works especially well when it's one-sided deterrence as it is with Iraq.  <br>
<br>
Think about it this way- if Iraq actually <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>had</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> WMD, the US and others would treat it with kid gloves and negotiate, much the same way as the Soviet Union was handled, and North Korea is currently being handled.  The fact that the US/UK are showing such belligerence is all but proof that Saddam poses <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>no imminent threat</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>the Iraqi government is not in compliance with 1441 and their cooperation has been selective at best. Iraq needs to show STRATEGIC cooperation, which it certainly has not.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Is there a time limit on compliance in 1441 Kad?  No, I didn't think so- explain to me again why time is of the essence?  Unless of course you're looking at war as a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>fait-accompli</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  There is no ticking clock if Saddam is being contained and deterred, no time pressure.  Disarmament is being achieved via inspections- I fail to see what the rush is.  Inspections are working, there is no time limit set, nor do I see the need for one.  Forces are in the region to help assure compliance as well as to up the containment/deterrence factor.  If results are being accrued now, then where is the need for war?<br>
<br>
&quot;It'll get hot in Iraq&quot; is no argument at all, because its premise is founded on a war taking place.  Remember also, that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>both</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> sides will suffer the effects of the heat, the US/UK forces are simply better prepared.  The heat favours us, not them because of equipment, training and resolve- for those reasons and because of the night attack factor.<br>
<br>
Plainly, there still isn't a case for war because the fundamental principles of why the status quo fails have not even been demonstrated at all.  I'll say it again- prove that containment or deterrence have failed.  That's all the first stage of a case for war needs to achieve to be credible- is it really that hard to draw up such a case?  The obvious is being overlooked- containment and deterrence <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>are</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> working and there is no imminent threat.  The fact that weapons exist does not equal a threat worth going to war for.  During the Cold war the USSR and United States each sat on enough WMDs to blow the entire planet to bits several thousand times over.  What happened?  Nada, because they mutually deterred one another.  With containment plus <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>one-sided</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> deterrence, why is there a threat posed this time- and where is the need for a war?<br>
<br>
 <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
